      "content": "The \"creepy\" thick roots are likely just the fig's way of trying to escape its current space, often called \"bound root\" issues when they become woody but not necessarily fatal. You generally shouldn't dig too deeply to inspect for unseen life, as the root system itself is usually the only sign of health needed to detect rot or pests early. Instead of trying to remove all soil contents, focus on carefully excavating only the exposed root ball you can see and smell for a critical, foul odor in your hands indicating hidden rot. Trimming only the damaged, black, or mushy spots during your repotting should be enough to prevent any hidden issues while saving your plant.",
